<br>
I've been on a couple breaks using this tactic exclusively. It has worked well. In fact I might suggest gathering the highest folks in one group or two and start the break an hour or two before the main force arrives.<br>
<br>
1. People won't get antsy waiting. One of the biggest killers of raids is lack of patience. Clearing those nasty roamers and settling the break in area before hand is a very nice way to ease the rest of the raid team in.<br>
<br>
2. 6 or 12 people are a heck of lot easier to manage than 35.<br>
As long as both groups have an evaccer and a diligent taunter to keep them from harm should be good. Give the evaccer free reign, best to port out at the first sign of trouble, too many adds, someone got zapped away from camp etc.<br>
<br>
3. Few things have been mentioned that are good tips. A west wall break, don't pull, they'll come to you. And for the love of ALL things holy, kill the scarelings first. They totally suck and will ruin a raid very easily. In fact when we used this tactic we had one group of 6 doing the work. Tank, Tank, cleric, cleric, druid, wiz. Two evaccers and two Ch'ers. If we got zapped out from a scareling and saw any adds coming, we evaccd. If by a stroke of luck the teleporting of the scareling did not cause adds we camped anyway. Granted we pretty experienced but this tactic can work.<br>
<br>
Once we did our thing bringing in the rest of the raid was simple stuff.<br>
<br>
Enjoy.<br>
